node.text: Omg I’m crying this is the sweetest thing and this brightened up my day ❤️❤️👍👍💯💯

***SWIPE👈🏻***
💗 Best. Dad. Ever! 👏🏻 You might wanna grab some tissues for this thread. 😢🤗 #DadGoals #FathersDay
.
@buzzfeednews: Aaron Gouveia says his 5-year-old son, Sam, loves to get his nails done by his grandma, but came home in tears because he was bullied for his polish. Gouveia was heartsick over his son's pain and decided to share the story to speak out against toxic masculinity. “While we've empowered girls to do and be anything, the same doesn't hold true for boys," Gouveia said. He wants all parents to "allow our boys to experience their full range of emotions without fear or shame.” 👏 (📷: Aaron Gouveia)
✊🏻✊🏼✊🏽✊🏾✊🏿🏳️‍🌈

Tears to my eyes. LOVE THIS

My son is a grown man (40) straight and married, but loves getting pedicures with his wife and his toe nails painted. He gets stares from strangers. I love it. Go Sam and thank you daddy for being such an understanding parent. ❤✌Be who you are.

Part of school is “socializing” which means enforcing roles and norms.  But sometimes people who deviate from the norms can lead the way.  I hope Sam can stay strong and lead others to empathy and love.

This had happend to me since a year ago. I had to recreate a movie poster for a class project, I chose Pulp Fiction because it's my favourite movie, so, I dressed up like Mia Wallace with the dress, wig, lipstick and nail polish. After I took the picture I took everything off except for the nail polish, because I actually liked it. Like a month after my stepmother bought me a blue nail polish because the color that I used didnt match me. Because of this it was more obvious that I painted my nails because the other color was more subtle and this triggered the people to say really sexist things, even my mother told me that "It isn't normal" only because society says that nail polish is a "girls thing". At the moment I don't have my nails painted because of work but if it wasn't for that I would keep them beautiful. This kid is really really really brave to stick to what he likes rather to what the society tells him to do. I also congratulate this parents to raise non hateful human beings, well done!
I read the whole thread and he is so right.
💛💛💛 what an awesome dad. I hope his message is spread far and wide.
Best Dad Ever 🙋🏻‍♀️😭 @melissabishh

Almost this exact thing happened to my little cousin who I think of as my little brother and since we don't live together I can't always be the positive force in his life that he needs. His parents don't really want to deal with things that are important to his well-being like how he expresses himself. So he ended up conforming to gender norms and now pokes at other kids with little quirks because that's what he's learned he should do. It really makes me sad since I was the one who basically raised this child. Long story short, his mother didn't really want to take on any motherly responsibilities when she gave birth to her child since "she just wasn't feeling it". I was ten at the time so I was fine with another kid hanging around, and that kept pace for years. We'd eat together, sleep together, play together, and we'd learn together. It got to the point that he started calling me "mother", and I didn't mind so I let him. That was about the time when he was going to start kindergarten and when he took his test it was brought to light that I was doing pretty great job with brain games and exercises of that nature together with him. He was shown to have and have a abnormally progressed IQ for his age and a really good comprehension rate. That's when his mother decided to jump in and take responsibility because she wanted the super smart kid that I practically raised all on my own without having to do any of the raising herself. Unfortunately, she took me out of the picture and started half-assing his at home lessons which caused his high learning curve to dull down in a year and a half, but since he was still above-average as a kindergarten child I guess she didn't have any qualms with it. She really beat into him that she was his mother, I was his cousin, I was not his big sister, and tried to make him think that we aren't very close. Now he is almost nine. He has grown up with a outwardly possessive mother in public but a lazy non-active mother at home. He has been punished way too often and taught in the wrong manner. So now he lashes out, and since his internet is not even slightly childproofed he is learning about serial killers and brutal murders. (P1)
So much ♥️ for this post. We have a similar nail polish story with my twelve-year-old boy. It’s heartbreaking. Let’s #breakthemasculinitymold !
What a wonderful family.
Omg I’m crying this is the sweetest thing and this brightened up my day ❤️❤️👍👍💯💯
